Teste do backend (R e Python) com escolha de engine por job

1) Subir serviços
- docker compose up -d db redis backend workek


2) Migrar banco
- docker compose exec worker python manage.py makemigrations
- docker compose exec worker python manage.py migrate


3) Criar dados mínimos no shell Django
- docker compose exec worker python manage.py shell

No shell:

from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model
from apps.projects.models import Project
from apps.shapefiles.models import StudyArea
from apps.jobs.models import Job

User = get_user_model()
user = User.objects.create_superuser("admin", "admin@test.com", "admin123")

project = Project.objects.create(owner=user, name="Teste", isotope_type="d13C")
print("Project:", project)

sa = StudyArea.objects.create(
    name="amazonia_legal",
    file_path="/data/shapefiles/amazonia_legal.shp",
    is_preset=True,
)
print("StudyArea:", sa)

# ==========================================================
# ETAPA A — Geração de rasters (gen_rasters)
# Troque execution_engine para "r" ou "python"
# ==========================================================
job_rasters = Job.objects.create(
    project=project,
    created_by=user,
    job_type=Job.JobType.GEN_RASTERS,
    status=Job.Status.PENDING,
    config={
        "execution_engine": "r",      # ou "python"
        "study_area_id": sa.id,
        "study_area_name": sa.name,
        "shapefile_path":  sa.file_path,
        "variables":       ["tavg"],
        "resolution":      "10",
        "skip_existing":   True,
    }
)
print("Job rasters:", job_rasters.id, "| status:", job_rasters.status)


from apps.jobs.tasks import gen_rasters_task
gen_rasters_task.delay(job_rasters.id)

# ==========================================================
# ETAPA B — Geração de isoscape (run_isoscape)
# Troque execution_engine para "r" ou "python"
# ==========================================================

job_iso = Job.objects.create(
    project=project,
    created_by=user,
    job_type=Job.JobType.RUN_ISOSCAPE,
    status=Job.Status.PENDING,
    config={
        "execution_engine": "r",      # ou "python"
        "dataset_path": "/data/datasets/madeiras.csv",
        "raster_dir": f"/data/rasters/{project.id}/{sa.name}",
        "response_col": "d13C_wood",
        "lat_col": "latitude",
        "lon_col": "longitude",
        "uncertainty": "quantile_rf",
        "resolution": "10",
    }
)
print("Job isoscape:", job_iso.id)

from apps.jobs.tasks import run_isoscape_task
run_isoscape_task.delay(job_iso.id)

4) Ver logs do worker
- docker compose logs -f worker

5) Conferir status do job no shell
job_rasters.refresh_from_db()
print(job_rasters.status, job_rasters.error_message)
job_iso.refresh_from_db()
print(job_iso.status, job_iso.error_message)

6) Debug do problema "Carregando rasters..."
- Verifique se o diretório tem .tif:
  docker compose exec worker bash -lc 'ls -lh /data/rasters/1/amazonia_legal/*.tif'

- Rodar script R manualmente (sem espaço no caminho de raster-dir):
  docker compose exec worker Rscript r_scripts/run_isoscape.R \
    --job-id test \
    --dataset-path /data/datasets/madeiras.csv \
    --raster-dir /data/rasters/1/amazonia_legal \
    --output-dir /data/isoscapes/test \
    --response-col d13C_wood \
    --lat-col latitude \
    --lon-col longitude \
    --uncertainty quantile_rf \
    --resolution 10

Observações importantes
- O worker agora registra no log qual engine foi usada: [engine] r, [engine] python, ou [engine] r (fallback).
- Se o script Python falhar e SCRIPT_ENGINE_FALLBACK estiver ativo, ele tenta R automaticamente.
- Scripts Python ainda não são 100% equivalentes ao pipeline R para todos os cenários; use R como referência de produção até validar paridade.